[3] Maine (Cumberland county)
Date: Sat 3 Nov 2018
Source: Kennebec Journal and Morning Sentinel/centralmaine.com, Portland Press Herald report [edited]
https://www.centralmaine.com/2018/11/02/scarborough-school-officials-issue-whooping-cough-warning/


Following a pertussis outbreak at Scarborough High School [Cumberland county], parents are urged to keep kids home if they have a cough and to update family vaccinations. An outbreak of whooping cough at Scarborough High School last month [October 2018] has health officials warning parents to take precautions.

Three high school students had confirmed cases of pertussis in October [2018], but none of the cases appeared to be connected, Superintendent Julie Kukenberger said. "We obviously want to be hyper-vigilant so families can be aware and take steps to protect their children," she said. Pamela Gill and Lisa Verzoni, both registered nurses, sent an email Friday morning [2 Nov 2018] to the Scarborough school community on behalf of the health services staff. "Students attending the high school may have been exposed," the nurses wrote. "It is important to inform the entire school community of the recent pertussis cases."

Schools in neighboring York county reported a spike in the highly infectious disease in September [2018], according to the Maine Center for Disease Control and Prevention. While cases reported statewide are down so far this year [2018] -- 262 through September compared to 317 during the same period last year -- 97 cases this year [2018] were in York county alone, and 25 of those cases were reported in September [2018].

The nurses recommended keeping children home from school and other activities if they have a cough and may have been exposed to pertussis. Other recommendations included making an appointment with a health care provider as soon as possible and informing them if a child has been exposed to pertussis. They also urged everyone to make sure their families' vaccinations are up to date.

[Byline: Kelley Bouchard]

--
Communicated by:
